snippet.textDisplay: This is vintage stuff. She deserves all the accolades she can get. Being an artist in her generation, could not have been easy; but to have stuck with it all, and continued to sing and sing so expertly and so melodiously, in spite of her age--it really blows my mind. And there is so much sraddha for music in this rendition--she sings because she loves music, she venerates singing, not because she is out for any kind of commercial gain. That purity shines through, and her reverential feeling for melody. Overwhelmed.
snippet.textOriginal: This is vintage stuff. She deserves all the accolades she can get. Being an artist in her generation, could not have been easy; but to have stuck with it all, and continued to sing and sing so expertly and so melodiously, in spite of her age--it really blows my mind. And there is so much sraddha for music in this rendition--she sings because she loves music, she venerates singing, not because she is out for any kind of commercial gain. That purity shines through, and her reverential feeling for melody. Overwhelmed.

snippet.textDisplay: This music is sublime. I got to know of this song through a Whats App music network called Swarayatra. It is one of the most sublime expressions/explorations of the raag Yaman, and the words are some of the most eloquent I have ever heard. One of the best songs ever--one that you want to keep listening to over and over again. Few songs truly bring tears to one's eyes--this one does for me. Who is the lyricist?

snippet.textDisplay:
She is clearly struggling to sing the song which probably made her career but that the ethereal beauty of the whole thing. Thats what age does to you and it is so SO beautiful. Showing her heydays was a master stroke.
